<DATE>
<P>
October 10, 1990, Wednesday, San Diego County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 1; Column 2; Metro Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
608 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN DIEGO AT LARGE: COULD WE GET A FEW AIRCRAFT CARRIERS IN THE PARKING LOT? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ANTHONY PERRY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A San Diego labor union wants you to think of Saddam Hussein before you shop at 
a grocery market in Linda Vista owned by an Iraqi. 
</P>
<P>
The union is asking for a boycott of a store owned by Victor Najor by comparing 
him to the Iraqi dictator. 
</P>
<P>
The dispute began more than a year ago when employees at Najor's stores in the 
Linda Vista and Nestor neighborhoods of San Diego voted to be represented by 
the United Food &amp; Commercial Workers Union, Local 135. 
</P>
<P>
But Najor and the union have yet to agree on a contract. Now the union has 
mailed out a flyer complete with a picture of Hussein: 
</P>
<P>
"Worried about the hostages in Iraq? What about the hostage situation in your 
own neighborhood?" 
</P>
<P>
On the flip side: 
</P>
<P>
"Victor Najor, an Iraqi businessman and owner of the Victory Foods store in 
your neighborhood, is holding his employees hostage -- to inferior pay, 
inferior conditions of employment and little or no job security. 
</P>
<P>
"The United States Government has conducted a democratic election of the 
employees of Victory Foods, and they voted to be represented by a union. But 
negotiating a contract with Victor Najor is like negotiating with Saddam 
Hussein." 
</P>
<P>
There's more: 
</P>
<P>
"As a community, let's help Victory Foods' employees fulfill their rights as 
free Americans! Boycott Victory Foods." 
</P>
<P>
Najor, one of 8,000 Chaldeans (Christian Iraqis) who have settled in San Diego 
County in recent years, has had other problems, too. A rowdy stomped on a Saudi 
Arabian flag hanging in one of his stores. 
</P>
<P>
Najor isn't around to discuss the union flyer. He's on his way home from a trip 
to Israel with a church group. 
</P>
<P>
His partner and attorney won't talk. Neither will the labor union. 
</P>
<P>
One neighbor who received the flyer says it persuaded her to start shopping at 
Victory Foods: 
</P>
<P>
"I think the flyer is offensive. Whatever the labor dispute, I think it's 
outrageous to mention that Najor is an Iraqi and smear him with a picture of 
Saddam Hussein." 
</P>
