<P>
JANE BYRNE EYES CHICAGO RACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHICAGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Former Mayor Jane Byrne says she will attempt a comeback in 1991 and already is 
circulating nominating petitions. 
</P>
<P>
"We are absolutely having no difficulty getting signatures," she said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
Byrne was elected mayor in 1979 and lost a reelection bid in the 1983 
Democratic primary to Harold Washington, who went on to become the city's first 
black mayor. 
</P>
<P>
She lost a comeback bid to Washington in the 1987 primary. 
</P>
<P>
Mayor Richard M. Daley, elected in 1989 after Washington died in office, is 
expected to seek a full four-year term in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
"Anybody can run for mayor," Daley said when asked about Byrne's decision. 
</P>
