<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD; 
</P>
<P>
COMMUNISTS OPPOSE CHANGES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
MOSCOW 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Defiant Communist officials said today they oppose widespread private property 
and indicated the party will resist calls to give up its own vast holdings and 
share power in a coalition government. 
</P>
<P>
The officials, briefing reporters on a two-day Central Committee plenum that 
ended Tuesday, also rejected the elimination of party cells in the work place 
and said the Soviet Union will continue to celebrate Revolution Day as a 
national holiday. 
</P>
<P>
Vladimir A. Ivashko, the party's No. 2 leader after Mikhail S. Gorbachev, said 
private property "will have to be restricted for quite a while" and "it is a 
process of privatization, not a one-time act or decree." And Politburo member 
Alexander Dzasokhov quoted party economists as saying just 7% of all property 
should be transferred to private ownership in the next 10 to 12 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Vladimir A. Ivashko 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
