<HEADLINE>
<P>
BEN JOHNSON TRADING SPIKES FOR SNOWSHOES? 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TORONTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ben Johnson may trade his spikes for showshoes -- yes, snowshoes -- and compete 
for Canada in the 1990 Nordic sprint championships. 
</P>
<P>
Nick Akers, executive director of the Canadian Amateur Snowshoe Assn., said 
Tuesday his group has invited Johnson to compete in the championships in 
Edmonton, Alberta, on Dec. 9. 
</P>
<P>
"I think Ben would add a lot of credibility to the sport, because I don't think 
you can find any snow-shoers in the world who would come close to him," Akers 
said. "We expect Johnson to finish in under 12 seconds." 
</P>
<P>
American Scott Hannay holds the 100-meter snowshoe record: 15.06 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
Johnson was stripped of the gold medal in the 100 meters in the Seoul Olympics 
after testing positive for anabolic steroids. 
</P>
